EDA¶

Background¶

The Fashion-MNIST dataset is an improved version of a classic neural entwork training set, the MNIST hadnwritten digits set. \ According to the Keras docs,

This is a dataset of 60,000 28x28 grayscale images of 10 fashion categories, along with a test set of 10,000 images. This dataset can be used as a drop-in replacement for MNIST.

The original MNIST dataset was a similar set of 60,000 28x28 grayscale images as well, also with 10, 000 test images. The ony differnece was that it contained hadnwritten digits instead of clothing items.

The reason the Fashion-MNIST set was created as a "drop-in replacement" for MNIST was because it was too easy to score well on, consisting of images made up of simple lines and curves. With a more complex setting like clothings with different sizes and patterns, the Fashion-MNIST is more analagous to the more modern applications of Computer Vision and can help set a more realistic benchmark for practical purposes

# Creates appropriately sized plt subplot for a number of desire axes
from math import ceil


def create_subplots_axs(n_plots, n_cols=3, plot_h=2, plot_w=2):
    n_rows = ceil(n_plots / n_cols)

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(
        nrows=n_rows, ncols=n_cols, figsize=(plot_w * n_cols, plot_h * n_rows), constrained_layout=True
    )

    ## add .flatten() method to flat subplots
    if not isinstance(axs, list):
        axs = np.array(axs)

    ## turn off plots on the grid that aren't being used 
    for ax in axs.flatten()[n_plots:]:
        ax.set_axis_off()

    return fig, axs
In [ ]:
def plot_class_agg(images, label_indexes, agg_func, **visual_kwargs):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 10, constrained_layout=True, figsize=(10 * 2, 1 * 2))
    class_labels = label_indexes.columns

    for ax, label in zip(axs, class_labels):
        agg_images = agg_func(images[label_indexes[label]], axis=0)

        ax.imshow(agg_images, **visual_kwargs)
        ax.set_title(label)

    return fig, axs

def plot_learning_curves(history, metrics=["accuracy", "loss"], yranges=[[0.5, 1], [0, 2.302]]):
    if isinstance(history, keras.callbacks.History):
        epochs = list(range(1, history.params["epochs"] + 1))
        history = history.history
    elif isinstance(history, pd.DataFrame):
        epochs = list(range(1, len(history) + 1))

    fig = make_subplots(
        rows=ceil(len(metrics) / 3),
        cols=min(3, len(metrics)),
        subplot_titles=[f"Model {metric}" for metric in metrics],
    )

    showlegend = True
    for i, metric in enumerate(metrics):
        row = (i + 3) // 3
        col = (i % 3) + 1

        fig.add_trace(
            go.Scatter(
                x=epochs,
                y=history[metric],
                name="train",
                showlegend=showlegend,
                line={"color": "blue"},
            ),
            row=row,
            col=col,
        )
        fig.add_trace(
            go.Scatter(
                x=epochs,
                y=history[f"val_{metric}"],
                name="val",
                showlegend=showlegend,
                line={"color": "orange"},
            ),
            row=row,
            col=col,
        )

        if yranges[i]:
            fig.update_yaxes(range=yranges[i], row=row, col=col)

        showlegend = False

    fig.show()

def plot_confusion_matrix(model, X_test, y_test, labels, ax=None):
    y_pred = np.argmax(model.predict(X_test), axis=1)

    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(
        y_test,
        y_pred,
        display_labels=labels,
        cmap=plt.cm.Blues,
        xticks_rotation="vertical",
        normalize=None,
        ax=ax
    )

With 6000 samples per class, I decided to set aside 500 of each for the validation set. \ Although this number is half the size of the test samples for each class, I feel that 500 'practice questions' is still a sizable amount of samples to estimate the performance of the models. \ In addition, since deep learning models are known to be data-hungry and scale well with more data, I am hesitant to take away too many samples from the models and deprive them of the ability to scale their results \ \ Hence, I will proceed with 5500:500 train:validation ratio, and off to train the models we go

Baseline Fully-Connected Network¶

Starting with a baseline network, I chose to use an extremely simple single 100-neruon hidden layer fully-connected network. \ \ The choice of such a simple baseline can be useful in setting a 'bare minimum' for any more complex design decisions we make down the line. \ Having something so basic can help highlight and contrast just how much benefit an increase in the amount of parameters and computation time brings \ and help us decide what changes are worth the cost. \ \ In addition, as the start of the series A/B testing that will follow, I'll take this chance to see how scaling changes the way a simple model like this learns

In [ ]:
plot_learning_curves(relu_FCNet_history)
plot_learning_curves(relu_FCNet_scaled_history)

Comparing the curves, the unscaled network (upper) has more trouble learning than the scaled network (lower). \ \ After 10 epochs, the unscaled network has only attained an validation accuracy of about 84% and a loss of 0.47 \ Meanwhile, with the same amount of training, the scaled network attained an accuracy of about 90% and a loss of 0.24. \ In addition, the validation accuracy curve for the scaled network is a lot less stable than the scaled network's. \ \ A likely explanation for this is that with smaller inputs, the network will overall have lower activations as well (since we're using ReLU) and hence \ when backpropagation is applied and the derivates are calculated with repeated multiplication, the scaled network will have smaller updates and take more \ controlled steps towards a more reasonable miniumum \ \ Either way, scaling has an empirical effect on improving the performance of a model and hence I'll be scaling my inputs for the other models from now on

Modified Practical CNN¶

With the performance of a simple CNN established, let's now see what a slightly more complex architecture can do.

First, inspired by VGG blocks, I increased the number of convolutional layers from 1 to 2 blocks of 2 and added max pooling layers between them. \ Doing so can hopefully help the model abstarct out more visual features from the images, ideally things like the smaller collars of Coats or wider chests of Shirts. \ I also decreased the kernel sizes from 5x5 to 3x3, since doing so will decrease the number of parameters while allowing for a deeper network, which is perfect for wanting to \ improve generalisation \ \ In additino, I inserted another dense layer at the bottom to add another layer of abstraction between the final convolutions and the output to hopefully \ draw out more complex patterns

Regularisation¶

Dropout Layers¶

The first technique I'll be using is Dropout, where some of the connections between layers are temporarily turned off at random. \ I find this regularisation technique the most fascinating (hence why I'm starting with it) as the possible justifications for why it works are all \ simple to accept intuitively (unlike most of Deep Learning and its tensor mathematics) \ and it has demonstrated to be wonderfully effective in more complex applications. \

There are a few explanations as to why Dropout works. First, dropout possibly prevent neurons from relying on each other too strongly. Since the connection between neurons can be cut at anytime, the model has to update \ each neuron in such a way that all of them will minimise the loss function in some way. This makes it so that every neuron learns to fit the data set instead \ instead of just letting a specific subset do the heavy lifting \ Another explantion is that by dropping out connections, we are essentially training different models with their own varied number of neurons. Then, at predict time, these models \ with their own learned wieghts work with each other to predict the image, basically ensembling a collection of trained neural networks. \

However, Dropout is in practice turning off parts of our model, so it still has to be applied carefully otherwise we might end up taking away all of the capabilities of our network. \ This is usually addressed by dropping out connections closer to the output as these are usually the ones that learn the quickest by virtue of being closer to the cost function and thus most likely to reap the benefits of dropout

Neuron Dropout¶

Starting with regular dropout, which sets the activations out of some neurons to zero. \ I applied dropout selectively to only the dense layers as is common practice in CNNs since removing single neurons in a convolutional layer \ isn't as dramatic due to the realtionship between multiple adjacent pixels in a filter.

In [ ]:
dropout = Sequential()

Model Evaluation¶
In [ ]:
dropout = keras.models.load_model("./checkpoints/dropout.h5")

In [ ]:
plot_learning_curves(dropout_history)

With Dropout applied, the regularising effect is immediately apparent. The learning curves start to diverge from each other fter epoch 30 instead of at epoch 6 and the validation curves remains close to the training curve up to epoch 60, where EralyStopping cuts it off. \ The highest achieved train accuracy has gone down, signalling that the model isn't strating to memorise the train set and the validation accuracy has gone up to 93% \ Overall, the regularising effect of Dropout is amazing, with little to no additional cost in train time or params

In [ ]:
plot_confusion_matrix(dropout, X_val, y_val, labels)

Looking at the confusion matrix, with Dropout the performance has drastically improved, with all classes getting at least 400/500 correct. \ Mistakes everywhere other than the typical few are practically non-existent now, and improving from here on out jsut involves differentiating \ between different types of upper body wear and between sneakers and ankle boots (both of which are fairly ambiguous tasks)

Final Metrics: 93.8% val_acc, Shirts: 416/500 (to non-regularized)

Spatial Dropout¶

Spatial Dropout works on the same principles as regular dropout but applied to filters instead of single neurons, making it more suited to Convoltional layers

In [ ]:
spatial_dropout = Sequential()

spatial_dropout.add(fashion_input)
spatial_dropout.add(pixel_scaler)
spatial_dropout.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
spatial_dropout.add(SpatialDropout2D(0.3))
spatial_dropout.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
spatial_dropout.add(SpatialDropout2D(0.3))

spatial_dropout.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
spatial_dropout.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
spatial_dropout.add(SpatialDropout2D(0.3))
spatial_dropout.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
spatial_dropout.add(SpatialDropout2D(0.3))

spatial_dropout.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
spatial_dropout.add(Flatten())
spatial_dropout.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
spatial_dropout.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
spatial_dropout.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

spatial_dropout.compile(
    optimizer="adam", loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"]
)

spatial_dropout.summary()

Weight Regularization¶

Another type of regularisation is weight regularisation, where we add the magnitude of the weights into the cost function, essentially telling the model \ to prefer smaller weights. This is similar to the AIC and BIC scores under maximum likelihood estimation, telling us how well the model likely estimates the true fit.

In [ ]:
weight_regularize = Sequential()

weight_regularize.add(fashion_input)
weight_regularize.add(pixel_scaler)
weight_regularize.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
weight_regularize.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
weight_regularize.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

weight_regularize.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
weight_regularize.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same", kernel_regularizer="l1_l2"))
weight_regularize.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

weight_regularize.add(Flatten())
weight_regularize.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer="l1_l2"))
weight_regularize.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer="l1_l2"))
weight_regularize.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

weight_regularize.compile(
    optimizer="adam", loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"]
)

weight_regularize.summary()

weight_regularize = keras.models.load_model("./models/weight_regularize.h5")
weight_regularize_history = pd.read_csv('./histories/weight_regularize.csv')
In [ ]:
plot_learning_curves(weight_regularize_history)

The curves show a a disapoointing result, with the model faring worse with L1 and L2 regularization applied. \ Although the learning curves are tighter, their magnitudes are nowhere near the non-regularized model's and are definitely worse than the other regularisatin method's. \ This means that large and specific activations are not the factors holding the model back and by adding weight regularization I seemed to have confused the model even further

In [ ]:
plot_confusion_matrix(weight_regularize, X_val, y_val, labels)

As pointed out, the model performed worse then without regularization and is even more confused when confronted by the prvious troublemakers.

Final Metrics: 86.2% val_acc, Shirts: 250/500 (to non-regularized)

All Together Now¶

Although both Dropout and Spatial Dropout showed improvement, they still showed signs of overfitting after more epochs. \ Perhaps if we use both at once, we can keep the learning vcruves tighter for more epchs.

regularize = Sequential()

regularize.add(fashion_input)
regularize.add(pixel_scaler)

regularize.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
regularize.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
regularize.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))


regularize.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
regularize.add(SpatialDropout2D(0.3))
regularize.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
regularize.add(SpatialDropout2D(0.3))
regularize.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))


regularize.add(Flatten())
regularize.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
dropout.add(Dropout(0.5))
regularize.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
dropout.add(Dropout(0.5))
regularize.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

regularize.compile(
    optimizer="adam", loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"]
)

regularize.summary()

Deeeper¶

With the empirical effects of dropout established, we can attempt to make our netwrok deeper to try and raise the ceiling on its performance

Changes made:

  • Added am additional convolution block
  • Added BatchNormalization to speed up convergence of model
In [ ]:
deeep = Sequential()

deeep.add(fashion_input)
deeep.add(pixel_scaler)
deeep.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
deeep.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
deeep.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

deeep.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
deeep.add(BatchNormalization())
deeep.add(SpatialDropout2D(0.3))
deeep.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
deeep.add(BatchNormalization())
deeep.add(SpatialDropout2D(0.3))
deeep.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

deeep.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
deeep.add(SpatialDropout2D(0.3))
deeep.add(BatchNormalization())
deeep.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
deeep.add(SpatialDropout2D(0.3))
deeep.add(BatchNormalization())
deeep.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
deeep.add(SpatialDropout2D(0.3))
deeep.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

deeep.add(BatchNormalization())
deeep.add(Flatten())
deeep.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
deeep.add(Dropout(0.5))
deeep.add(BatchNormalization())
deeep.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
deeep.add(Dropout(0.5))
deeep.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

deeep.compile(
    optimizer="adam", loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"]
)

deeep.summary()

Data Augmentation¶

Since the models have improved but are still overftting, we can try another regularization method: Data augmentation. \ We can apply linear transformations to the data to change its pixel values while retaining its subject, essentially creating fresh data. \ \ I chose to apply horizontal flips to create more variety to handle the cases with Sneakers we found during EDA and random rotations up to pi radians \ since any more will be equivalent to some other rotation + a horizontal flip \ So with our model overfitting, perhaps these methods could help it focus less on the training set and more on generalising patterns

In [ ]:
from keras.layers import RandomFlip, RandomRotation
In [ ]:
data_augmentation = [
    RandomRotation(factor=(0, 0.5)),
    RandomFlip("horizontal")
]

deeep_layers = [l for l in deeep.layers]

augment = Sequential([fashion_input] + deeep_layers[:1] + data_augmentation + deeep_layers[1:])

    optimizer="adam", loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"]
)

Optimisers¶

Since the attempt at data augmentation failed, I decided to stick with the deeper model and train it until it reaches a maximum performance. \ And while we're at it, perhaps we can investigate how different optimisers control how models learn by seeing how they push the model to the maximum

Adam¶

So with our model overfitting, perhaps these methods could help it focus less on the training set and more on generalising patterns \ One of the main ways the Adam optimizer drives the model to convergence quickly is through the idea of momentum. It stores an weighted sum of past gradients to build up a sense of how much the model is moving from iteration to iteration and adds it to the calculated gradient. This is a very natural definition of momentum - accumulating the magnitude of previous downward steps.\ Using a momentum like this, perhaps the model can be pushed even further to improve its performance

\ The learning rate has also been decreased to make sure the model doesn't step too far too quickly now that we have gotten past the inital stages

NAdam¶

While Adam tries to accumulate past gradients, Nadam uses a different definition of momentum to drive models to convergence. Nadam uses the gradient of the previous iteration to estimate where the model will end up after the current iteration and uses the new position to further inform the calculated gradient.\ It essentially tries to look ahead of the model and keep it updated using future in addition to past steps. With such a different take on the definition of momentum compared to the classic idea, it would be interesting to see how such a method might improve the performance of the model \

The learning has also been decreased for this test

In [ ]:
def plot_shirts(plots, plot_nums, cols, title=None):
    fig = make_subplots(
        rows=len(plot_nums) // cols, cols=cols, vertical_spacing=0.00000000000000001, horizontal_spacing=0.00000000000000001
    )

    for n, image in enumerate(plots[plot_nums]):
        fig.add_trace(
            px.imshow(image, binary_string=True).data[0],
            row=int(n / cols) + 1,
            col=n % cols + 1,
        )

    if title:
        fig.update_layout(title=title)

    fig.update_xaxes(showticklabels=False)
    fig.update_yaxes(showticklabels=False)
    fig.show()
